commit.message:
Enhance ppc64-diag to use IPS version of device tree properties

Currently, ppc64-diag uses model and system-id properties to fetch
machine model and serial number.

Use /proc/device-tree/ibm,vendor-model and
/proc/device-tree/ibm,vendor-system-id to fetch model and serial values
if present. Else, fallback to the original method of using
/proc/device-tree/model and /proc/device-tree/system-id properties.

Signed-off-by: Sathvika Vasireddy <sv@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

commit.message:
diags/diag_nvme: call_home command fails on nvmf drive

The diag_nvme command needs to retrieve the VPD log page from NVMe for
filling in the product data while generating the call-home event.
However, call-home feature is supported for directly attached NVMe
module. In the current diag_nvme implementation, if user doesn't
provide NVMe device name for diagnostics then it(diag_nvme)  loops
through each NVMe moudle (directly connected to the system/LPAR as
well as discovered over fabrics) and attempt retrieving the SMART log
page as well as VPD page.  Unfortunately, diag_nvme fails to retrieve
the VPD page for NVMe connected over fabrics and that causes the
diag_nvme to print "not-so-nice" failure messages on console.

Henec fixed the diag_nvme code so that for call-home event reporting,
it skips the NVMe which is connected over fabrics and prints a
"nice-message" informing the user that it's skipping diagnosting for
NVMe module connected over fabrics.  In a nutshell, with this fix now
diag_nvme would only diagnose the NVMe module which is directtly
attached (over PCIe) to the system.

Signed-off-by: Nilay Shroff <nilay@linux.ibm.com>

ppc64-diag/lp_diag: Enable light path diagnostics for RTAS events

Currently, Light Path Diagnostics support is enabled only for OS and
Enclosure type events. Enable light path diagnostics support for RTAS
type events by turning on only the high priority FRU callouts.

Signed-off-by: Sathvika Vasireddy <sv@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

ppc64-diag/lp_diag: Utilize trim_trail_space() function in event_fru_callout()

Update the event_fru_callout() function to use the trim_trail_space()
function to be able to remove any trailing spaces from the location code.
This change aims to address an issue where the presence of trailing spaces
in the location code results in failure to find an indicator for the given
location code. Use trim_trail_space() on the location to ensure that the
device location code is properly compared with the indicator list.

Signed-off-by: Sathvika Vasireddy <sv@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

ppc64-diag: Move trim_trail_space() function to common/utils.c

Currently, trim_trail_space() function is used in diags/diag_nvme.c file
to be able to trim trailing white spaces from a given location code. Allow
code reusability by moving the trim_trail_space() function from
diags/diag_nvme.c to common/utils.c.

rtas_errd: Handle multiple platform dumps

Currently, whenever a new dump arrives, old dump file of that specific dump
type is removed before writing the new dump out. Any dump file with the
same prefix (dump type) gets deleted. This means only one set of dump files
is saved, since only one dump file per dump type is saved.

Handle multiple dumps on Linux by allowing as many dumps to be offloaded
until disk space is available. To do this, remove the function that checks
for prefix size and removes old dump files. In the event of not enough
disk space available, log an error to the user along with the dump tag.
User will free up space and run extract_platdump tool using the dump tag
provided in the error message to offload the dump. Error log can be viewed
by the user by issuing 'journalctl -p err -t rtas_errd' command.

Signed-off-by: Sathvika Vasireddy <sv@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

ppc64-diag v2.7.9 release

    Major changes since v2.7.8:
    - Add NVMe diagnostics support.
    - Update travis build to use fedora37 and Ubuntu22.10
    - Few minor bugs fixes.

Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

Fix syntax and minor change in configure.ac

In commit fecb120, by mistak I added extra closing bracket and the wrong
package name in AC_MSG_FAILURE macro.

Fixes: fecb120 ("Update build dependency to use libvpd >= v2.2.9 due to ABI change.")
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

travis: Switch from Ubuntu20.04 to Ubuntu22.10

Starting with ppc64-diag version v2.7.8, there have been CI failures with
ubuntu 20.04 docker container. ppc64-diag now depends on new libvpd library
version v2.2.9 which is not part of ubuntu 20.04 and hence the CI failures.

Ubuntu 22.10 ships the latest libvpd package which makes it perfect for
travis CI builds.

Update .travis.yml to use ibm-cloud as group so that travis can trigger
POWER9 VM instead of POWER8 VM where Ubuntu22.10 docker is failing. This
is because Ubuntu22.10 is supported only on POWER9 and above.

Also, update Dockerfile to install pkg-config package to fix existing
travis CI failures on Ubuntu.

Signed-off-by: Sathvika Vasireddy <sv@linux.ibm.com>
[mahesh: minor change in commit log]
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

travis: replace Fedora 33 with Fedora 37

Starting with ppc64-diag version v2.7.8, there has been CI failure with
fedora 33 docker container. ppc64-diag now depends on new libvpd library
version v2.2.9 which is not part of fedora 33 and hence the CI faulires.

Fedora 37 ships with latest libvpd package which makes it perfect for
travis CI builds.

commit.message:
scripts/ppc64_diag_mkrsrc: Fix partition ID for LE OS releases

When running the 'od' command to retrieve the partition ID from the
device tree on a litte-endian OS the result isn't properly displayed.
For example on a partition with ID 3 the following is seen:

$ od -An -td /proc/device-tree/ibm,partition-no | sed "s/\\s//g" 2>/dev/null
50331648

The result is 50331648 (0x03000000) when the expected is actually 3
(0x00000003). This issue is not seen in big-endian OS releases where the
value retrieved is properly displayed. So add --endian=big flag to
address this issue for LE releases and keep the same behavior seen in BE
releases:

$ od -An -td --endian=big /proc/device-tree/ibm,partition-no | sed "s/\\s//g" 2>/dev/null
3

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>

diags/diag_nvme: Trim trailing white space in sl_callout fields

The string fields in sl_callout struct can't have white spaces or it
will break the current way the servevent_parse.pl script works in which
the input is split using a space separator. So any extra white space
will cause the fields to move around.

If IBM VPD data is extracted from NVMe log page 0xF1 it is right padded
with white spaces, so the strings needs to be trimmed.

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>

diags/diag_nvme: Enable diag_nvme build and limit its scope

Add makefile changes required to build the diag_nvme code and a man page
describing the command usage. Also add a script to run the diag_nvme
tool and install it to run as a cron daily job.

The scope in which this tool should be executed is limited to P10 Power
VM LPARs.

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>

common/platform: Add function to identify processor version

Add a function to identify what processor version is in the system. This
is done by looking into the Processor Version Register (PVR) first two
bytes.

The PVR is a more reliable way to detect this given processor in compat
mode would display a different processor version, but still label the
proper PVR.

For example a P10 processor running in p8compat mode:
processor       : 0
cpu             : POWER8 (architected), altivec supported
clock           : 3600.000000MHz
revision        : 2.0 (pvr 0080 0200)

As opposed to what it would be displayed if it was not in compat mode:
processor       : 0
cpu             : POWER10 (architected), altivec supported
clock           : 3600.000000MHz
revision        : 2.0 (pvr 0080 0200)

So use this information to properly label which processor generation is
in use.

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>

diags/diag_nvme: Add extra data to logged event through raw_data

The raw_data field from the servicelog event allow to add extra
binary data to the logged event in the database. With it we can add
SMART and VPD data that was collected from the device which we are
generating the event.

The data itself is formatted as follows so it provides an extensible way
to add more data in the future if needed:

The raw_data format is made of sections, each section contains a
one-byte tag which identifies what is the data contained in this
section, an additional one-byte reserved and two-byte length which
represents the length value (in bytes) of all the data fields contained
in this section, followed by the data items, so a section has the
following format:
+------------+----------------------------------------------+
|   Offset   |                Field meaning                 |
+------------+----------------------------------------------+
|   Byte 0   |               Identifier Tag                 |
|            |                                              |
|   Byte 1   |                  Reserved                    |
|            |                                              |
|   Byte 2   | Length (in bytes) of data - bits[7:0] (LSB)  |
|            |                                              |
|   Byte 3   | Length (in bytes) of data - bits[15:8] (MSB) |
|            |                                              |
| Byte 4 - N |                 Data items                   |
+------------+----------------------------------------------+

The current tags in use are the following:
+---------+------------+
| Tag 01h | SMART data |
+---------+------------+
| Tag 02h |  VPD data  |
+---------+------------+
| Tag FFh |  End Tag   |
+---------+------------+
For the end tag (FFh) no additional data items are present along with
the header, so it is a section with other header bytes set to 0.

Each data item consists of a four-byte header followed by some amount of
data. The format of this header is as follows: a keyword is a
two-character (ASCII) mnemonic that uniquely identifies the information
in the field, one additional reserved byte and the last byte of the
header is binary and represents the length value (in bytes) of the data
that follows. The keyword data is provided as ASCII characters. The
following is an example:
         |      +0       |      +1       |      +2       |      +3       |
         |               |               |               |               |
         |7|6|5|4|3|2|1|0|7|6|5|4|3|2|1|0|7|6|5|4|3|2|1|0|7|6|5|4|3|2|1|0|
         +-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+
         |            Keyword            |   Reserved    |   Length (N)  |
Byte 0 ->|                               |               |               |
         +-------------------------------+---------------+---------------+
         |               Data (byte 4 -> N+3, example here N=4)          |
Byte 4 ->|                                                               |
         +---------------------------------------------------------------+

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>

diags/diag_nvme: Read SMART data from a file

Add an option to read the SMART data from a file instead of the device,
this can be used as a test mechanism, given injecting errors into a
device SMART log is not possible at this moment.

In case this option is used and the file pointed to can't be opened,
treat it as the failure to read SMART data from the device. Otherwise
process the SMART data contained in the file and use it for the
diagnostics of the device. In case failures are detected report the
events in the servicelog database.

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>

diags/diag_nvme: Add option to dump SMART data into a file

This patch adds an option to dump the SMART data from a device into a
specified file in a key=value format.

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>

diags/diag_nvme: Add config file to select which events to report

Add a configuration file to allow customization of which events should be
reported by the diagnostics tool. The file is in a simple key=value
format, values not defined in the configuration file will be enabled by
default by the tool.

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>

diags/diag_nvme: Warn excessive write on NVMe device

If a customer is writing to an NVMe device at an excessive rate, it
could wear out the device prior to its expected lifespan so estimate the
current write rate based on the number of data units written and powered
on hours from the SMART data and compare it to the device endurance in
"Drive Writes Per Day" (DWPD), if the rate exceeds this value generate
a warning event in the servicelog database.

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>

diags/diag_nvme: Report SMART data critical warning bit events

In case the SMART data has critical warning bits enabled report an event
in the servicelog, the only recoverable bit is the temperature one, if it
is the only one detected report as a warning event in the servicelog. If
any other bit is set to 1, bump the severity of the event to an error and
report all the bits set to 1 as part of the description.

Signed-off-by: Murilo Fossa Vicentini <muvic@linux.ibm.com>
